1 timothy 2:15 ¬†¬†  notwithstanding she shall be saved in childbearing , if they continue in faith and charity and holiness with sobriety .
the medical tax credit ( like most tax credits ) is based on the lowest tax rate , not your marginal rate .
so on that basis it is generally accepted that the lower income spouse will claim give the lower threshold .
for 2016 the threshold is the lower of 3 % of income or $ 2,237 .
meaning that the lower income spouse earning $ 50k can claim a 15 % credit on all expenses above $ 1,500 .
while the spouse earning $ 100 k can only claim a 15 % credit on all expenses above $ 2,237 .
which means by having the lower income spouse claim the credit they will receive a $ 110.55 higher tax credit ( 15 % x ( $ 2,237 - $ 1,500 ) .
so other than one spouse not having any taxable income to apply the tax credit , i am not aware of any scenario where the higher income spouse would claim the credit .

while the criminal law - writing the criminal code and other criminal statutes as well as criminal procedure per section 91(27 ) of the .constitution act 1867 : 

 " the criminal law , except the constitution of courts of criminal jurisdiction , but including the procedure in criminal matters " 

 the provinces have jurisdiction over these sorts of police investigations and the charging decisions per s. 92 ( 14 ) - the administration of justice : 

 " the administration of justice in the province , including the constitution , maintenance , and organization of provincial courts , both of civil and of criminal jurisdiction , and including procedure in civil matters in those courts . "
as noted bc operates under a crown counsel charge approval system which is an exercise of provincial jurisdiction .
this ensures that police do not get away with sloppy work and it is lawyers who make the decision .

no it does n't .
at least , not in the argument set forth by the church .
essentially , we are told that because we do not know definitively that a blastocyst is not a complete , ( in the sense of being ensouled ) human person , we are morally obliged to treat it as though it is such , because in the course of natural development , barring misadventure , it will become a human person .
this is an argument in favor of moral caution .
it is an assertion that a human life in the form of   soul - less zygote is morally equivalent to the life it might become ten months down the line .
moral caution is a good thing , but it does not license the assertion that all abortion is , factually , murder .
further , if it is moral caution that we attempt to follow , then we are obliged to consider the broader moral ramifications of outlawing abortion , in a way we would n't have to , if abortion were   murder proper .

could it be that what you describe as " new agey type words " is simply modern english , as opposed to archaic english en route to obsolescence .
also , could it be that you simply prefer the comfort of lyrics we seniors were raised with , rather than the modern and fast evolving english that our youth prefer .
as for " lord " being replaced by " god , " i presume you are talking about the psalms and other ot scripture ?
if so , there is some history behind the change that is important .
when we read " lord , " the hebrew was often " yahweh " ( actually the hebrew only has the consonants yhwh ) .
the jews and modern scholarship recognizes this as the name of god , so by the normal rules of translation of names from one language to another , we ought to read " yahweh " rather than " lord " in english translations .
indeed the new jerusalem bible , used in catholic liturgies in great britain , always correctly translates yahweh as yahweh .

another option would for each state to require that its electoral votes would go proportionally to the popular vote in that state so that multiple candidates could win at least some of a state 's electoral votes .
that would get rid of the winner - takes - all nonsense and shift the campaigns away from focusing entirely on a tiny handful of ' battleground ' states to having to focus on all states .
right now a conservative never bothers to campaign in california because there 's zero chance of them winning those 55 votes .
but in the proportional system , trump would have taken about 18 of those votes due to his 32 % of the popular vote there .
conversely , clinton would have taken 16 of texas ' 36 votes due to her 43 % of the vote there .
in this way , every state would be a battleground state and the candidates would be motivated to campaign nationwide rather than just in a half dozen states .
heck , maybe we 'd even see a presidential candidate visit alaska ! (
clinton would have taken 1 of our 3 )

among the unmerited gifts of my life was gregory 's tutelage in toronto .
his weaving the personal and social dimensions of faith together has had a lasting impact .
once in conversation he offered an observation that has long helped me understand diverse pulls in the church .
we were reading johannes baptist metz , and he grounded that remarkable thinker 's life 's work in a personal question , offering a clarifying contrast .
metz and ratzinger were roughly the same age , raised in nearby bavarian villages .
their early social and religious experiences so similar , yet their life work so different .
the holocaust set the question with which metz has grappled ever since :   how was it possible that , in such devout catholic setting , fervent , believing catholics offered so little , if any , resistance to the rise of absolute evil in history ?
whereas ratzinger felt deeply the loss of that peasant catholicism in the face of modernity .
one of those concernss became gregory 's , too .

the perkins loan program , formerly the national defense student loan program was established in 1958 and the stories of those who benefitted form the then 3 % student loan interest level are historic .
mostly used for those going in to the profession of teaching , they had their doors of opportunity opened .
over the many year the loan interest remained low and rose to a 5 % level but with such benefits as teaching in low income areas would provide offsets for the payment of the loan .
that program ws manageable and operated at the offices of financial aid .
it was a revolving fund and worked well , and default rates were again guarded well by the colleges .
yes , the economy has changed   but the concept of student aid managed by the institution always worked well and reviews were conducted by the feds to ensure the same .
all concerned need to look at the continuation of this perkins loan program for indeed it " did make a diffenrce . "
i know , for i was one of the aid officers .

garrison , 

 where are you getting your numbers ?
without making any claims about criminality or good or bad consequences , the number of muslims in norway has almost trebled and the percent of the population ( 1.3ish to 3.0 % ) more than doubled in the last 30 years .
it went from having probably no more than 10 k total adherents in the ' 80s , to 50 k + in the ' 90s , to being the second largest professed faith today with approaching 150k registered members and a projection of doubling both population and percentage of population in another decade .
that is rapid change , not some kind of status quo , driven largely by immigration of people from , setting aside religion , a markedly different cultural background into what was a fairly homogeneous culture .
that said , i 'd ascribe any claims of increased criminality more to the fact that many immigrants are young and male , which is the cohort that commits most crimes regardless of race / culture , and to the known issues of social strain due to immigration .

" what should canada do ? "
start by smartening up on stuff grade school kids know , but our politicians apparently do n't .
like canada 's northern latitude,-- which means a high subsistence cost because of the need for heat , light , and foods that do n't grow very well in snow .
how smart is it to enter a " free trade agreement " with a country such as mexico , whose costs are so much lower than ours because of this ?
how smart is it to tax carbon that both individual canadians and our industry depend on for basic needs such as heating for almost half the year ?

we also need to strip away regulatory red tape strangling industry , the result of politicians trying to outdo each other with their moral exhibitionism .

interesting , and important , story austin , thanks .
in the late 70s and through the 80s i reffed basketball and umpired baseball and softball in eugene , and our associations provided officials for rural schools -- as far away as oakridge and elkton .
some of the most fun , and biggest challenges , i ever had as an official was working those small schools .
gyms that were also the cafeteria / auditorium , with endlines barely four feet wide -- and a padded wall awaiting .
baseball diamonds surrounded by trees , incredibly picturesque -- but for the angry fans in pickups who might follow us out of town for a bit after losing a close game ( only a couple times ) .
but for all that , it was a great slice of rural oregon , until -- as you note -- mills began to close and storefronts began to shutter on many small main streets .
coming to the end of an era is always hard , as your piece suggests .
brought back some good memories .
thanks .

i see several posts saying that toronto should raise residential property taxes .
it 's completely misleading to say that a toronto homeowner pays " less " taxes than eg :   the 905 .
what people are comparing is property tax rates , not the total tax bill .
the rates are per a phased in market value assessment .
therefore , toronto homeowners have seen a disproportionate rise in their property taxes as a result of the appreciation of their homes .
this means their total tax bill is proportionately higher for a physically similar property .
eg :   a 1 million dollar house in mississauga might be worth 5 times that if it were dumped into the middle of toronto .
using my own home as an example , i pay ( rounding down ) about $ 12k / year in property taxes ( i 'm including our separate garbage collection fee ) .
for that , i get old services .
eg :    i had to replace the old clay sewer line this year at a cost of $ 10 k ( city maple 's tree roots encroached and broke the line ) .
healthcare should not be anymore of a private industry than is national defense .
spain is mishandling this badly with its strongarm approach .
it should be negotiating with the catalan government , not dismantling it !
imagine if the canadian federal government dissolved the national assembly in quebec - that would drive moderates into the hands of the separatist movement .
arrangements set up by negotiation have to be updated by negotiation in democracies .

the prevalence of user fees is the direct result of the braying of the " no new taxes " crowd .
.
the result is that taxation is not spread evenly , is highly capricious , is highly regressive , and very often yields perverse economic incentives .
.
taxes are at a 60 year low .
they are not yielding the revenues required to provide the public sector goods and services needed to optimise overall economic growth in our society .
.
if we want out economy to grow , taxes need to go up fairly substantially .
.
how much higher ?
a rough guess would be 4 % - 5 % of gdp higher , possibly quite a bit more .
how do we know ?
because we have a rapidly ageing population , and we are in a transition to higher density , more highly urbanised population centers , and over the next 30 - 50 years we are going to have to pay for that transition .
.
the good news is that the faster we do it the sooner that   expenditure will yield a richer , more energy efficient , knowledge - based economy .

i do n't believe darwinian macro - evolution is a working hypothesis that allows explanations or predictions of any sort .
adaptation or micro - evolution does allow some predictions and can be observed in nature , for example the different beak sizes and shapes of darwin 's finches .
however , macro - evolution as proposed by darwin and his followers has never been observed to create new species .
there is no point in using a theory that is not true ( darwin 's ) to try to explain what we see .
we would just be propagating error .

i am not a supporter of the child benefit program ( and i have 4 kids ) - however , it is simply illogical to exclude those types of expenditures when determining what it costs to raise a child .
most if not all of the expenditures you list grow incrementally as you add children to the household .
including the need for additional bedrooms , resulting in larger homes and higher property insurance bills .
additional or larger cars with car / booster seats , higher vehicle insurance and licencing costs .
more consumption of electricity , water , and even heating with kids in the home during office hours .
house maintenance is higher on a larger home not to mention the inevitable additional wear and tear .
no matter what your position is on the program it is laughable to suggest that anyone is " profiting " from the amount received .

so you think there was n't a single rational justification for the age - old , virtually universal definition of marriage as one man , one woman ?
what hubris .
your citation of article 10 of the declaration of human rights does nothing to support you cause .
the right to marry is fundamental in the united states as well , and yet it woud have been though laughable , until recently , to say that this fundamental right to marry included the right to marry someone of the same sex .
why ?
because " marriage , " by definition , meant one man , one woman ( although in some instances , polygamy ) , but never man - man or woman - woman .
note , by the way , that the declaration , article 10 , says " without any limitation due to race , nationality or religion . "
it does not forbid a prohibition on grounds of sex , meaning man marrying man or woman marrying woman .
indeed , such a prohibition would have been though absurd when the declaration was passed in 1948 , because the very idea of such " marriage " was absurd .

according to fars data reported by nhtsa , fatal crashes due to distracted driving involving use of electronics such as cell phones are about 3 % ( 12 % of   25 % ) of total fatalities .
this compares with 31 % involving an intoxicated driver , yet similar penalties are proposed .
moreover , this does not differentiate between hand - texting , hand - held talking , and hands - free talking .
i would guess the crashes almost entirely involve hand - texting , since phone conversations differ little from conversations with passengers that account for 1.25 % ( 5 % of 25 % ) of recorded fatal crashes .
i can not find any data justifying prohibition of hand - held or hands - free talking .

i do n't understand the 6 mutations conclusion you have .
mutations occur at a low rate for sure ( 1 mutation in 300 genomes for bacteria ) .
so the chance of two mutations is 1/300 x 1/300 and the chance of 6 mutations is ( 1/300)^6 , or 1 in 79 trillion .
but the number of bacteria on earth is 5,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 , so 6 billion bacteria will have 6 new mutations arising at any time .
given a generation time of 20 minutes , that is searching a lot of genome space every year .
this does n't even take into account that there are 6 billion billion bacteria with 2 mutations arising at the same time , and most of these will pass those mutations on to the next generation , allowing 2 additional new mutations to arise in 6 billion of those , and then 6 bacteria to have all 6 new mutations after just 3 generations .
most new genes arise from duplication and subfunctionalization ( also work of u of o researchers ) , so no one wonders how a gene with 1000 amino acids could appear at once .

nunes did not say that trump 's phones were tapped .
he said exactly the opposite of what you have desperately and erroneously concluded from this article . "
incidental " means that trump was recorded while talking persons who were under surveillance as part of a national security investigation .
telephone conversations have two or more parties .
if the phone of one of those parties is tapped , then everyone who is part of the conversation is recorded .
that 's what " incidental " means .
before you start mistakenly gloating , you might ask why trump is talking to people who are subjects of   fisa approved wire taps and what those conversation might reveal .
this is not good news for trump .

the age class distribution of the pine - spruce - fir stands in the mountain parks is   very skewed to the older , over mature , decay dominated age classes .
this situation is detrimental for several reasons . :
firstly , these stands produce large amounts of   co2 in respiration , often more than they consume in photosynthesis , leading to net positive co2 balance .
further , these stands , which nature would have replaced via pyral ( fire ) driven processes are effectively biological deserts , with little understory vegetation for ungulates like moose , deer , elk to forage on .
further still , as these stands age they build up unhealthy amounts of decayed woody fuel in their understory so that when fire occurs , it is devastatingly hot and destructive often leading to volatilization of such micro nutrients as boron , manganese etc .
even further , the pine species in these produce serotinous cones which require fire to unleash their seeds .
fire in these stands is not destructive , it is regenerative .

 nonsense !

quite a few years ago i was in this group ( mostly women except for me ) and this one woman who was a fairly vocal feminist ( not in an obnoxious way , but everyone knew where she stood ) happened to mention how unfair it was that women had to pay more for annuities than men .
having worked at a life insurance company at one point , i understood how these things worked .
since women on average live longer than men , they ended up paying more .
so , foolish me , i assumed she was talking about getting rid of gender as a ratings criteria .
so i observed that obviously men would then stop paying more for life insurance ( living shorter lives , etc . ) .
oh no , she replied , that 's completely different .
that has informed my opinion of feminism and in the 25 or so years that have passed since then , i 've never seen or heard a single thing to contradict it .

actually there is such a thing as presumed consent .
if a court is presented with evidence that two people had sex together , and no evidence about consent or lack of it , the court will presume that both parties consented .
this comes up in the family law context , where evidence of sexual activity is often necessary to , for instance , show that there is good reason to order paternity testing , or to prove adultery .
if a man seeking divorce on the grounds of adultery can show that his wife had sex with some other man , the court will presume she did so willingly unless presented with evidence to the contrary ( if a woman is the victim of rape , the act of intercourse involved is not considered adultery ) .

i suppose any state 's unemployment rate could be better ( or worse )   if you excluded specific community members 
 however ,   the key concept is that the population is made up of three parts : 
 people who are employed , people who are unemployed , and people who are not part of the 
 labor force .
only the people actively looking for work are considered 
 unemployed and make up the rate .
retirees , for example , stay - at - home parents who choose not to work , or those living where they can not be actively seeking work are among those considered outside of the labor force .
so , those living in rural alaska who " refuse " to move as you put it .. are not making the   unemployment rate any higher .

you 're right in saying that this is unprecedented for the earth .
that said , it is most certainly unprecedented for the human race .
climate has definitely changed in the past , but the rate that it 's changing and the effect that we 're having on natural levels of carbon dioxide is disconcerting .
our societies have adapted to live in a narrow range of climate with many cities located right on the coast , and enormous amounts of people dependent on stable climate for their water , food , and general livelihood .
here , i and so many other alaskans fish for salmon every summer for subsistence and commercial purposes .
it is a big part of what our state is about .
several studies have shown that the relatively minor natural climate cycle that affects us in ak , the pacific decadal oscillation , has major effects on salmon populations .
considering that there is a consensus that the climate is changing(even if you 're set on the idea that it 's natural ) , ought we not be concerned for our children ?

while a sad time for canada , slavery was n't as prominent here in canada as it was elsewhere .
canada had around 4,200 slaves during that period mostly purchase from the native nations themselves .
85 % of slaves were used in quebec .
france had around 250,000 during that period .
g&m also wrote an article about it back in feb 2014 , " 200 years a slave : the dark history of captivity in canada " .
it was based on quebec historian marcel trudel 's findings .
some additional context , pbs.org   wrote an article based on the trans - atlantic slave trade database , edited by professors david eltis and david richardson .
apparently , 10.7 million africans were shipped to the new world , but only 388,000 were shipped directly to north america ( ie u.s. ) .

the challenge is , land costs in vancouver are so high , that building a three bedroom apartment unit commands a resale price of well over a million dollars .
so working families looking for an affordable housing model are still priced out .
the second issue is the commodification of housing here in metro vancouver .
it is more lucrative for developers to build small one bedroom units , and lots of them - and in turn sell them to investors or speculators , or simply those that want to deposit money ( overseas or otherwise ) into a tidy little safety deposit box .
outside of metro vancouver - yes townhouses and multi - bedroom units become more affordable due to lower land costs , and are more available as they are a viable alternative for working families .

i do n't think this will be material on the true ' small ' business owner , since the costs of accounting for small incomes and managing to defer tax are n't likely worth the gains because their marginal tax rates are also low .
the greatest pushback ( and likely most organized and vocal lobby ) will come from those with the most to lose .
they can afford the accounting , and access the specialized products to make them count to reduce taxes .
from expensing large ul policies which include cash savings that can be withdrawn tax free , to deducting vacations , they benefit vs. a similarly paid employee in a very material way .
as a result , higher income earners are growing ever more likely to change business structures to gain from less tax .
my brother lives in calgary , and his oil company employer laid him off , paid for his accounting to set up his company , and worked through a complex array of compensation .
end result , less cost for oilco , more cash for him , paid for by less tax for society
